04216nam a22006015i 9780271064291DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710642917 a10.1515/97802710642912doi  a(DE-B1597)584057  a(OCoLC)1253313132  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aNAT0100002bisacsh04a820.936bS1572211 aScott, Heidi C. M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChaos and Cosmos :bLiterary Roots of Modern Ecology in the British Nineteenth Century /cHeidi C. M. Scott. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Beyond the Dichotomy -- tPART 1 Chaos -- t1 Romantic Chaos: Natural Patterns Disturbed -- t2 Victorian Chaos: Industrial Disruptions -- t3 Today's Science Nonfiction -- tPART 2 Microcosm -- t4 Romantic Microcosms: Brain Worlds -- t5 Victorian Microcosms: Domestic Systems -- t6 Today's Scientific Modeling -- tPART 3 Keats and Ecology: A Case Study -- t7 The Literary Empiricist -- t8 Hyperion: The Chaos of Tartarus -- t9 Microcosmic Odes -- tEpilogue -- tWorks Consulted -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Chaos and Cosmos, Heidi Scott integrates literary readings with contemporary ecological methods to investigate two essential and contrasting paradigms of nature that scientific ecology continues to debate: chaos and balance. Ecological literature of the Romantic and Victorian eras uses environmental chaos and the figure of the balanced microcosm as tropes essential to understanding natural patterns, and these eras were the first to reflect upon the ecological degradations of the Industrial Revolution. Chaos and Cosmos contends that the seed of imagination that would enable a scientist to study a lake as a microcosmic world at the formal, empirical level was sown by Romantic and Victorian poets who consciously drew a sphere around their perceptions in order to make sense of spots of time and place amid the globalizing modern world. This study's interest goes beyond likening literary tropes to scientific aesthetics; it aims to theorize the interdisciplinary history of the concepts that underlie our scientific understanding of modern nature. Paradigmatic ecological ideas such as ecosystems, succession dynamics, punctuated equilibrium, and climate change are shown to have a literary foundation that preceded their status as theories in science. This book represents an elevation of the prospects of ecocriticism toward fully developed interdisciplinary potentials of literary ecology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074525240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271064291zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271064291423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271064291.jpg  a978-3-11-074525-2  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK